In this proclamation, President Barack Obama declares April 2014 as National Child Abuse Prevention Month in the United States. The proclamation highlights the importance of giving every child a chance at a happy and successful life and acknowledges the burden of abuse and neglect that hundreds of thousands of young Americans face. The President emphasizes the role that each individual has in preventing child abuse and helping young victims recover. He encourages Americans to be aware of warning signs of child abuse and neglect and provides a website for more information on prevention. The proclamation also mentions the efforts of the administration to raise awareness, strengthen responses to child abuse, and support research into its causes and consequences. The President calls upon all Americans to observe the month with programs and activities that help prevent child abuse and meet the needs of children.